column4: Forrestdale & Thomsons Lake (WA035) whole site overview
column12:
Ramsar typology classifies as inland type P wetland - described as seasonal/intermittant freshwater lakes > 8Ha. ECD describes as brackish, seasonal lakes with extensive fringing sedgeland, occuring between dunal systems, dominant natural water source is groundwater, weakly coloured to clear and neutral to slightly alkaline pH
Ramsar Criteria 1-representative, rare or unique example of a natural or near-natural wetland type found within the appropriate biogeographic region, Criteria 3 - supports populations of plant and/or animal species important for maintaining the biological diversity of a particular biogeographic region
column24: Soil is sand over pyritic peaty sediment. Water regime is tending towards longer dry periods and lower max depths. Vegetation is open water sorrounded by sedgelands with flooded gum moving into Tuart moving up the gradient. Salinity ranges from fresh to brackish in spring to saline as it dries out in summer.

column38: Drying climate and water abstraction have lead to reduced periods of inundation and removal of suitable conditions/habitat for resident and migratory waterbirds and has lead to terrestrialisation of fringing areas and weed encroachment across the ecosystem. Other threats include predation of waterbirds and quenda from cats and foxes
column40: Drying climate and water abstraction is leading to reduced periods of inundation and removal of suitable conditions/habitat for resident and migratory waterbirds and is also leading to terrestrialisation of fringing areas and weed encroachment across the ecosystem. Other threats include predation of waterbirds and quenda from cats and foxes and dieback in the banksia woodlands surrounding the lake
column41: A summary of the major threats includes: • Maximum water depths at both lakes are substantially lower, the period of inundation substantially less, and annual drying is occurring earlier than at any time in the past; • The introduced Bulrush Typha orientalis now covers expansive areas of the waters edge and is encroaching across the dry lake beds at both lakes; • The number of waterbirds and number of species recorded at Forrestdale and Thomsons Lakes have been variable, but overall have declined in recent years; • Total phosphorus levels have declined and subsequently associated blue-green algal blooms (cyanobacteria) and midge swarms have also declined

column4: Vasse-Wonnerup System: Seasonal brackish/saline estuarine lagoons
column24:
Seasonal brackish/saline Vass and Wonnerup estuaries have become lagoons due to the floodgates, which allow floodwater to flow out but are managed to minimize seawater getting in. The Vasse and
Wonnerup estuaries are 9 and 5 km long and up to 0.6 km wide and typically < 1 m deep even during
winter. Exit channels are around 2 m deep. During winter flood flows, the estuaries are
connected by the narrow Malbup Creek once water levels exceed 0.8 m AHD
